    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "06aea2ab_cb0c129d",
        "filename": "resultdb/proto/rpc/v1/recorder.proto",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 219,
      "author": {
        "id": 1134874
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-12T22:03:26Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "No, I meant, isn\u0027t that behavior valid /now/: validateBatchCreateTestExonerationsRequest errors if for each individual CreateTestExonerationRequest, it has invocation populated and doesn\u0027t match, which means that if we have some individual CreateTestExonerationRequests with invocation /not/ populated, and others that /are/ populated and match, validation will pass.\n\nIt seems that if a user passes inconsistent requests[i].invocation (or request_id), that would be unintentional and we could arguably error on it. We don\u0027t currently, and it would be more complexity to check, so the (non-blocking) question is if we want to.",
      "parentUuid": "0e43ea0a_f7c66cf9",
      "revId": "acc3f8254660216cffffb0ecb5ac91e59a7ecd86",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "31bae186_79cfc16f",
        "filename": "resultdb/proto/rpc/v1/recorder.proto",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 219,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-12T22:20:39Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "i see what you mean. https://aip.dev/233#request-message does not have this recommendation, but I am not opposed to making the API stricter than that (it is a superser of strictness implied by the guidelines). if we really want to prevent weird behavior, we should probably prohibit setting subrequest.invocation entirely (why would one send a request with invocation set at two levels?). Would you prefer that?",
      "parentUuid": "06aea2ab_cb0c129d",
      "revId": "acc3f8254660216cffffb0ecb5ac91e59a7ecd86",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa47a051_5bfd24db",
        "filename": "resultdb/proto/rpc/v1/recorder.proto",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 219,
      "author": {
        "id": 1134874
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-12T22:33:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Might a user generate CreateTestExonerationRequests and then depending on some condition decide whether to batch them or not, which would lead to two separate requirements of needing the invocation set or not?\n\nAlso this is definitely non-blocking for this CL!",
      "parentUuid": "31bae186_79cfc16f",
      "revId": "acc3f8254660216cffffb0ecb5ac91e59a7ecd86",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c05d5178_79369811",
        "filename": "resultdb/proto/rpc/v1/recorder.proto",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 219,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-13T02:30:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "there is a lot of things a client might do, including a lot of unreasonable things. Fortunately, we don\u0027t have to support all of them because they can still get their job done if they just generate request id *right after* they decided between batch and non-batch version of the RPC. I also have hard time imagining a case where the user would be making this choice to begin with. Most likely, if the client even bothers about batching, they\u0027d just use the batching version unconditionally. In which case, they wouldn\u0027t bother creating request id in sub-requests.\n\nthe current impl matches the recommendation, and it is already implemented. Let\u0027s land this.",
      "parentUuid": "fa47a051_5bfd24db",
      "revId": "acc3f8254660216cffffb0ecb5ac91e59a7ecd86",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
